				\begin{document}$${R_{\rm{D}}^{2}}$$\end{document}RD2 for the chosen “best” model. Relative survival estimates were obtained using flexible parametric survival models on the hazard scale with four degrees of freedom [19]. Relative survival was defined as the observed survival divided by the expected survival where the expected survival is obtained from national life tables stratified by age at diagnosis, sex and calendar year. United Kingdom life-time risk was estimated from data available from the Office for National Statistics (https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/lifeexpectancies/datasets/nationallifetablesunitedkingdomreferencetables). Statistical analysis was performed using SAS v9.4 (SAS Institute Inc., Cary, NC) and Stata IC v13 (StataCorp. College Station, TX: StataCorp LLC). Some graphs were drawn using Prism (v7 Graphpad Software Inc.).
